Availability: Docs
Title:Bloom
Crumbs:%ROOT%, Resources, Resources/Showcases/PostProcessing
Description:A rundown of how Bloom was employed within the Post Process Matinee example included with UE4.

[INCLUDE:Engine/Rendering/LightingAndShadows/LightsAndPostProcess#LightingAndPostProcess_Bloom] For this portion of the scene, bloom was employed in the following manner:

![](BloomSettings.png)


| **Property** | **Use in this scene** | **Before/After** |
|---|---|:---:|
| **Bloom Intensity** | In this case, a value of 0.3 was used to _dim_ the bloom down considerably from its default values.<br><br>More information about Bloom settings can be found in the [Bloom section of the Post Process Effects documentation](Engine/Rendering\PostProcessEffects\Bloom). | [INCLUDE:#bloom] |
| **Dirt Mask** <br><br><br> **Dirt Mask Intensity** <br><br> **Dirt Mask Tint** | The dirt mask gives the illusion of light being blocked and refracted by dirt or small debris on the lens of a camera. The effect can be seen in the real world when it is time to clean your camera lenses. <br><br> In this case, the texture, tint, and intensity work together to give a dim and very slightly cooled dirt effect to the bloom.<br><br>More information about Bloom dirt mask settings can be found in the [Bloom section of the Post Process Effects documentation](Engine/Rendering\PostProcessEffects\Bloom). | [INCLUDE:#dirt] |









